issue(id="0016" status="review")
  title Support ephemeral bootstrap without Tailscale enrollment
  user-story
    as-a scrubs operator booting disposable guests for testing or feature work
    i-want an explicit way to bootstrap an instance without enrolling it in Tailscale
    so-that short-lived guests do not accumulate stale tailnet nodes that I have to clean up afterward
  premise.
    Scrubs currently treats guest-side Tailscale enrollment as the default when
    a Tailscale OAuth client secret is configured for the selected clean auth
    profile. That is a good default for long-lived personal guests, but it is
    the wrong behavior for disposable instances created only to validate a
    change, reproduce a bug, or test bootstrap behavior.

    Today those ephemeral guests inherit the normal sealed Tailscale bootstrap
    path, register into the tailnet, and then leave cleanup work behind when
    the guest is deleted. The operator pain is not guest reachability during
    testing; Lima-local access through `limactl shell <instance>` and the
    existing host-local SSH path are already enough for many short-lived flows.

    The goal of this task is to add an intentional "ephemeral testing" path to
    scrubs bootstrap that suppresses guest-side Tailscale enrollment without
    weakening the current default for ordinary long-lived guests. That path
    should be explicit, easy to invoke, and documented clearly enough that
    operators do not need to remember ad hoc cleanup work after test runs.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs exposes an explicit bootstrap-time control for disposable guests that prevents Tailscale enrollment even when a host Tailscale OAuth secret is otherwise configured.
    criterion The default bootstrap behavior for ordinary guests remains unchanged: if Tailscale auth is configured and the operator does not opt out, the guest still enrolls as it does today.
    criterion The ephemeral opt-out path avoids installing or enabling the guest-side Tailscale autoconnect flow for that bootstrap, rather than merely registering and expecting later cleanup.
    criterion The operator-facing invocation is documented with examples for common disposable workflows such as testing bootstrap or validating a feature in a short-lived instance.
    criterion Validation for the new path includes confirming that a disposable guest still bootstraps successfully and remains reachable through the existing local scrubs access path without appearing as a new tailnet node.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      The operator control now uses an explicit bootstrap-time mode on the
      existing command surface. `just bootstrap` accepts a final
      `tailscale_mode` argument, defaults it to `tailscale-enabled`, and
      supports `tailscale-disabled` for disposable test guests without
      introducing a separate lifecycle profile or project-shim-only mechanism.
    item(status="covered").
      For now, the ephemeral path stays narrowly scoped to Tailscale
      enrollment only. Additional disposable-guest behaviors such as naming,
      cleanup commands, or suppression of other long-lived-only services can
      be introduced later as separate explicit options if real operator need
      emerges, rather than bundling multiple behaviors into this mode today.
